S ''Helianthus''''' from 1919 to 1939. She was named after the [[Helianthus]], the genus to which the sunflower belongs.<ref>''Sunset Western Garden Book.'' Leisure Arts. 1995. pp. 606–607.</ref>
==Construction== ''Helianthus'' was built as a private [[motorboat]] of the same name in 1912 at [[Bristol, Rhode Island|Bristol]], [[Rhode Island]], by the [[Herreshoff Manufacturing Company]]. She was delivered on the 11th of June, 1917.<ref name="Nav source"/>
==United States Navy service, 1917–1919== [[File:USC&GS Helianthus ca. 1925.jpg|200px|left|thumb|USC&GS ''Helianthus'' in [[Alaska]]n waters, ca. 1925. She flies the [[Flag of the United States Coast and Geodetic Survey|U.S. Coast and Geodetic Survey flag]] from her [[Mast (ship)|mast]] and the [[national ensign]] at her stern.]] The U.S. Navy acquired ''Helianthus'' from her owner, N. A. Herreshoff, on 11 June 1917 for [[World War I]] service as a [[patrol vessel]] and [[Ship commissioning|commissioned]] her on 6 July 1917 as USS ''Helianthus'' (SP-585) with [[Boatswain's mate (United States Navy)|Boatswain]] T. H. Rich in command.<ref name="Navy">{{cite web|title=Helianthus (S. P. 585)|url=https://www.history.navy.mil/research/histories/ship-histories/danfs/h/helianthus.html|website=www.history.navy.mil|accessdate=6 November 2016}}</ref>
''Helianthus'' was assigned to [[section patrol]] duty in the [[2nd Naval District]] during World War I. She operated on harbor patrol and harbor entrance patrol in [[Narragansett Bay]] and at [[Newport, Rhode Island|Newport]], Rhode Island.<ref name="Navy"/>
''Helianthus'' collided with the [[fishing vessel]] ''T.H.C.'' on 12 June 1918 off [[Warren, Rhode Island|Warren]], [[Rhode Island]]. The owner of ''T.H.C.'', the Warren Oyster Company, filed for $3,840.56 in damages, but was granted only $50.00 in compensation by the [[United States Congress]].<ref>{{cite book|title=Congressional Edition, Volume 7645|date=1919|publisher=U.S. Government Printing Office|location=University of California}}</ref><ref name="collision" group="note">A message was sent to the [[United States House of Representatives]] saying: {{Quote|text=SIR: I have the honor to transmit herewith, for the consideration of [[United States Congress|Congress]], in accordance with the provisions of the act of June 24, 1910 (Stat., p. 607), a communication from the [[United States Secretary of the Navy|acting secretary of the Navy]] of the 20th instant, submitting an estimate of appropriation, in the sum of $3,840.56, to pay for claims of damages by naval vessels adjusted by the [[United States Department of the Navy|Navy Department]].|author=Carter Glass|source=Congressional Edition Volume 7645}}
The [[Speaker of the United States House of Representatives|Speaker of the House of Representatives]] responded, writing: {{Quote|text=SIR: This department has considered, ascertained, adjusted, and determined the respective amounts due to claimants on account of damages for which vessels of the United States Navy were found to be responsible in the following described instances: *1. The owner of the boat ''T. H. C.'' for damages sustained by said boat as a result of a collision with the U. S. S. ''Helianthus'' S. P. 585, at Warren, R.I. on June 12, 1918, $50. The correspondence in the department indicates that the owner of the boat ''T. H. C.'' is the Warren Oyster Co. of Warren R. I.|author=Frederick H. Gillett|source=Congressional Edition Volume 7645}}</ref>
==United States Coast and Geodetic Survey service, 1919–1939== The U.S. Navy transferred ''Helianthus'' to the [[United States Coast and Geodetic Survey]] on 28 March 1919.<ref name="Nav source"/><ref>{{cite book|last1=Silverstone|first1=Paul|title=The New Navy, 1883–1922|date=2013|publisher=Routledge|isbn=9781135865436|page=217}}</ref> Commissioned as '''USC&GS ''Helianthus''''', she served as a [[survey ship|survey]] [[Launch (boat)|launch]] during her years with the Coast and Geodetic Survey, conducting [[hydrographic survey]] work primarily in the waters of the [[Territory of Alaska]].<ref name="NOAA">{{cite web|title=NOAA History – Tools of the Trade/Ships/C&GS Ships/HELIANTHUS|url=http://www.history.noaa.gov/ships/helianthus.html|website=www.history.noaa.gov|accessdate=6 November 2016}}</ref> The Survey sold her in 1939, and her subsequent fate is unknown.<ref name="Nav source">{{cite web|title=Helianthus (SP 585)|url=http://www.navsource.org/archives/12/170585.htm|website=www.navsource.org|accessdate=6 November 2016}}</ref>
